  "response": "Here are some examples of how the word \"intimation\" is used in a sentence:\n\n*   **She gave no intimation that she was unhappy with the arrangement.** (This means she showed no sign or hint that she was unhappy.)\n\n*   **The dark clouds gave an intimation of the coming storm.** (This means the clouds hinted at or foreshadowed the storm.)\n\n*   **He had received an intimation from his boss that his job was on the line.** (This means he had a subtle warning or indication that he might be fired.)\n\n*   **The novel's opening paragraphs provide an intimation of the tragic events to come.** (This means the opening gives a subtle clue about what will happen later.)\n\n*   **Despite her cheerful demeanor, I caught a faint intimation of sadness in her eyes.** (This means you perceived a slight hint or suggestion of sadness, even though she was trying to appear cheerful.)\n\nIn general, \"intimation\" suggests a subtle, indirect, or delicate hint or suggestion of something. It's often used to describe a feeling, a warning, a clue, or an indication that is not explicitly stated but is nonetheless present.\n",
